<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1461,1884]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1677,1703]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species was previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[858,1005,1677,1703]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[1051,1189,1677,1704]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont (1991)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[1201,1335,1677,1704]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont (1991)</bibRefCitation>
believes that 
<taxonomicName authority="Wiedemann" authorityName="Wiedemann" box="[201,615,1713,1739]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Anthomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tempestatum">
<emphasis box="[201,471,1713,1739]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Anthomyia tempestatum</emphasis>
Wiedemann
</taxonomicName>
, which was recorded by 
<bibRefCitation author="Al-Houty, W." box="[892,1081,1713,1739]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref29679" refString="Al-Houty, W. (1989) Insect Fauna of Kuwait. Kuwait; Fahad Al-Marzouk, Printing &amp; Publishing Establishment, Kuwait, 189 pp." type="book" year="1989">Al-Houty (1989)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1151,1236,1713,1739]" name="Kuwait" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Kuwait</collectingCountry>
, is in fact 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wiedemann" authorityYear="1824" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Anthomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tonitrui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">B. tonitrui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the Middle East it was recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[660,742,1749,1775]" name="Kuwait" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Kuwait</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[797,865,1749,1775]" name="Oman" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Oman</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[880,1000,1749,1775]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1461,1884]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,1785,1811]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Biological remarks.</emphasis>
The larvae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kowarz, 1873" authorityName="Kowarz. Several" authorityYear="1873" box="[588,691,1786,1811]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Brontaea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[588,691,1786,1811]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Brontaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
live in mammal dung and sometimes in bird droppings. They hatch in the second instar and are obligate carnivores. Adults of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wiedemann" authorityYear="1824" box="[805,921,1822,1847]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Anthomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tonitrui">
<emphasis box="[805,921,1822,1847]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">B. tonitrui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are attracted by faeces and carrion (
<bibRefCitation author="Gregor, F. &amp; Rozkosny, R. &amp; Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J." pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 280" refId="ref32614" refString="Gregor, F., Rozkosny, R., Bartak, M. &amp; Vanhara, J. (2002) The Muscidae (Diptera) of Central Europe. Folia Facultatis Scientiarum Naturalium, Universitatis Masarykianae Brunensis, Biologia, 107, 1 - 280." type="journal article" year="2002">
Gregor 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
) and they have been reared from human faeces (
<bibRefCitation author="Skidmore, P." box="[788,962,1857,1884]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref36277" refString="Skidmore, P. (1985) The Biology of the Muscidae of the World. Series Entomologica 29. Dr. W. Junk Publishers, Dordrecht, 550 pp." type="book" year="1985">Skidmore 1985</bibRefCitation>
) and also cow dung (
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C." box="[1201,1322,1857,1883]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref35020" refString="Pont, A. C. (1991) A review of the Fanniidae and Muscidae (Diptera) of the Arabian Peninsula. Fauna of Saudi Arabia, 12, 312 - 265." type="book" year="1991">Pont 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
